Setiing up os in aws

I am using red hat linux
 
create instance on aws, get public ip, add security for port 80,443,and port that will be used

now goto putty key gen,  select load, load .ppm(change file type to all. default is .ppk)
select generate private key, then save it in ssh folder

now goto putty, host name:ec2-user@35.153.25.7 , ssl, port 22
goto connection->ssh->auth and click on browse an select the .ppk(private key) that was generated earlier
goto session, save the session, and launch the session.

ru:  sudo yum update -y

now to install apache use: sudo yum install httpd , then, sudo systemctl enable httpd, then  sudo systemctl start httpd (installed path is /var/www)
verify it using:  sudo systemctl is-enabled httpd


Amazon Linux Apache document root is /var/www/html, which by default is owned by root.
To allow the ec2-user account to manipulate files in this directory, you must modify the ownership and permissions of the directory. 

Add user to apache group: sudo usermod -a -G apache ec2-user

Change the group ownership : sudo chown -R ec2-user:apache /var/www

change the directory permissions of /var/www and its subdirectories: sudo chmod 2775 /var/www && find /var/www -type d -exec sudo chmod 2775 {} \;
find /var/www -type f -exec sudo chmod 0664 {} \;



To test it is working fine: add a file welcome.txt inside /var/www/html and hit from web browser. 

Now we need to install php: sudo yum install php

goto /etc/httpd/conf and open httpd.conf and add the following line: LoadModule php7_module modules/libphp7.so (open with sudo vi)
sudo apachectl restart

sudo setsebool -P httpd_can_network_connect 1    //allow socket on php


To install mysql: sudo yum install mariadb-server , sudo yum install php-mysqlnd, sudo systemctl start mariadb, sudo mysql_secure_installation, 
sudo systemctl enable mariadb

sudo yum install wget
now to install mysql-server, use :sudo wget https://dev.mysql.com/get/mysql57-community-release-el7-9.noarch.rpm
then :sudo rpm -ivh mysql57-community-release-el7-9.noarch.rpm
then: sudo systemctl start mysqld
then: sudo systemctl status mysqld
then: yum install mysql-devel -y

to install gcc and gpp: yum groupinstall "Development Tools" , yum groupinstall "Development Libraries"